Just technical update of my old "Big Mek from Dawn of War" model (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3350534)

- more polygons for smoother shapes
- updated sculpts of the head, arm, and pants sculpts and some other minor details
- slightly adjusted the pose to make it look better on the table
- re-cut - for 3d printing etc

I want to clarify: this is not a "remake". This is a "remaster" of the old model - to be honest, i didn't even look at the character's pictures from the game while making this remaster. The goal, to use an analogy, was to try not to rework it, but just to "improve textures and fix bugs" — so it wouldn't be such an embarrassment for me anymore and could last for many years to come.

(NON COMMERCIAL of course)

Description :

 1
 2

Genetically engineered Marines travel throughout Space, battling depraved heretics, dishonourable traitors, and vile aliens.

This set includes 4 powered gauntlets, two holding the torn off heads of two different types of alien beast - a brutal ork, and a sinister soulstealer. The third holds a retro style space beaky helmet, and the fourth is empty, perhaps for you to add in your own head model! All four have supported versions.

This is an updated version of the first thing I ever tried to 'sculpt', as opposed to arrange geometric shapes - an ork head. It's a little reflection on my part, comparing where I started to where I am. It's been a slow process, as I take what digital hobby time I can in between physical modelling and all my other fickle interests! But it's still nice to see what I feel in some improvement.

You can see the original here:
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/power-gauntlet-prime-scale-powered-gauntlet-holding-head

I am an amateur enthusiast 3D designer, and appreciate all constructive feedback. Please check out my other designs for more wargame models, and please consider following me, posting a make, or even leaving a donation via my profile!

Alloteu (https://cults3d.com/en/users/Alloteu/3d-models) is the original designer of Lawdogs. Evilamericorp (https://cults3d.com/en/users/evilamericorp/3d-models) & Dimkaf (https://cults3d.com/en/users/dimkaf/3d-models) took his models, reposed them, and added additional bits to create alternate models.

I just took Evilamericorp's and Dimkaf's creations, removed the non-Lawdog stuff and collected them together so you could quickly access additional Lawdog models.

Note these guys have no heads! But I've included 3 of Alloteu's Lawdog Heads (with a ball, cylinder, or hole at the bottom) for you to use.

A griffin (or griffon, depending on the English spelling) is a mythological creature with the body of a lion and the head and wings of an eagle. It is a common figure in the mythology and art of various cultures, often associated with vigilance and the protection of treasures.
Characteristics:
Body:
The lower body of the griffin is that of a lion, including its tail and hind legs.
Head and Wings:
The upper body is that of an eagle, with a sharp beak, piercing eyes, and feathers.
Additional Attributes:
In some depictions, it is also attributed with pointed ears and eagle-like foreclaws.
Symbolism and Meaning:
Guardian:
Griffons are known to be guardians of treasures and riches, especially gold.
Strength and Courage:
Combining the strength of the lion and the sharpness of the eagle, the griffin symbolizes power, courage, and vigilance. Connection to the Sun:
In some cultures, the griffin is associated with the sun and light, due to the eagle's majestic nature.
Origin:
Griffins are believed to have ancient origins, possibly in the Middle East or Asia.
Depictions of griffins are found in the art and mythology of various civilizations, including Greek, Roman, and Persian.
There is speculation that the image of the griffin may have been inspired by dinosaur fossils.

For a variety of projects I've got on, I needed a set of human heads to add to models I intend to sculpt for 3D printing. I couldn't find any I like, so have made up a collection of heads I've created by scratch sculpting, using Blender Add-ons, etc. None are 'stock' generation. Each has been scratch sculpted, re-sculpted from add-on generated blank faces, modified, re-shaped etc by me to meet the needs of my projects for 28mm - 32mm scale miniatures. 

I really struggled to find any free base heads I could use as a starting block to model onto, so am putting these here as a resource for any other amateur enthusiast designers like me who need a start until our scratch-sculpting talents get to where they need to be!

If you do use them in your own projects, would love to see them.

---------------------------------------------------------

 The Tortuga Group, a heretofore relatively unknown defense contractor, recently unveiled an upgrade suite for the venerable Quixote-class mech chassis.

 Their Quixote Defense Upgrade Package is a long-distance take on the concept of mechanized walker warfare, with an emphasis on stand-off weaponry and heavy shielding. This may not be suited for the mechanized arenas of Junctionworld, but mercenaries on the open battlefields found throughout the worldgate networks are sure to benefit.

 The new Spina Mk.II C-Beam Cannon is devastatingly effective on distance targets, with the damage inflicted usually an inverse to the target’s proximity.

 For closer adversaries that slip past the C-Beamer, a Redmaw Persecutor-class Plasma Cannon dispenses superheated damage, though its recharge rate has caught some pilots short. Thus, a heavy flamethrower is also added to the Spina Mk.II for supplemental in-close coverage.

 Adding to the new upgrade’s enhancements is the Testudo VI Force Field projector, a variation on shielding systems found on heavier kaiju-fighting megamechs and titans. When properly modulated, this generator can be used to deflect heavy incoming fire, or lend its protection to nearby units.

---------------------------------------------

This kit includes...

1 Plasma Cannon with two optional barrels.
1 C-Beamer Cannon with Auxiliary Flamethrower
2nd Generation Weapon Arms and Upper Arms with support rims to add stability.
1 Force Field Generator with two options of flat magnetized mount or a peg compatible with Imperial Warrior and similar builds.

Enjoy!

Best,
John Bear Ross

When da Big Meks gettin' tired of walkin’ up to da enemy just to hit 'em, they built Shoota Botz – walkin’ fortress o’ dakka designed to turn battlefields into bullet storms wiff blasta beams n rokkits. Bristlin' with barrels, belchin' smoke, and covered in rivets, dis bot’s idea of a good time is shootin’ everything that moves... and then shootin’ it again, just to be sure.

From rokkits to rattlin’ big shootas or ork tek blastas, Shoota Botz got more guns than sense – which is just how da greenskins lovin' it. No choppy arms here, just pure ranged firepower, rainin’ lead from across da field while laughin’ like a mad git.

Note: Dis is a fan-made model, full of grimy character and orkiness, but not linked to any official game or company. It’s just for da ladz who like loud machines an’ big fights.

This model is compatible to the bitz of following models:
- Mosha Bot
- Brawla Bot


======= PRINTING =========

- Layer hight 0.05mm
- Use tree / organic supports.
- I printed my test prints with a 0.25mm nozzle (for best quality)
- Orientate the Exhausts01-04 vertical

======= Assembly =========

If you need instructions - just open all files in 3D Builder or e.g. Meshmixer at the same time (drag and drop). There you can have a look where they need to go in 3D.



---

Tersus

An updated version of my previous (now deactivated) file pack for a robotic arm which I made months back. Besides fixing some geometry and STL file issues which were present in the first pack, I also decided to add some additional details to it. The Wastes are home to all manner of terrible creatures, mutated from what were once the humble creatures of the forests. Whether this was by design, genetic mutation, or simply through exposure to chaotic magics is unknown.

This is a collection of mutated beasts, designed for Fantasy and Post-Apocalyptic Wargaming and RPGs. They are truly massive beasts, and so are provided both whole, in kit form, and with hollowed out versions to allow you to chose the right set for your needs. These were made whilst making my toad-dragon (link below), as each time I looked at it, it made me think of a different animal! I saw a rat, molerat, and hippo, and here they are!

I love settings in post apocalyptic fallout shelters, where desert mole rats have mutated into massive beasts, so have a particular fondness for the mole-rat monster here - perfect for creating a monstrous mount for your post apocalyptic raiders or travelling merchants!

The Toad Dragon can be found here:
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/chaos-toad-dragon

These models come without rider or saddle, and are designed to be kit-bashed with your favourite fantasy range. These parts are also compatible with the bits from the Toad Dragon, and so would complement it nicely.

Please see my other designs for other wargaming STLS, including maggots, tics and flies suitable for adding even more detail to this model, or to decorate your army's bases.

I am an amateur enthusiast 3D designer, and appreciate all support and constructive feedback. Please check out my other designs for more wargame models, and please consider following me, post a make, and enjoy my models. Hello everyone,
The Advent season is all about joy and giving, and I think it's just part of it to give others a little joy.

First of all, I would like to sincerely thank everyone who has supported me on Patreon over the past few years. Without your support, I probably wouldn't have taken the time to create some of my miniatures. It was a great motivation that helped me move forward - thank you so much!
But the time on Patreon has passed due to a lack of time. The fact that you have the opportunity to download these old publications today is primarily thanks to them.

<b>MyLinks: https://allmylinks.com/enfenix</b>

---
<p>General information</p>

My miniatures are designed to work out of the box with original 28mm Hero Quest miniatures.
I always add a version with Heroquest base and one without a base. The weapons and the base are only combined (if possible). If you need different HeroQuest-style base, you should check out my customizer:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4299465

Personally, I now prefer 32mm miniatures. I usually scale them to 112% -115% directly in the slicer.

I am happy about every shared make, especially the painted ones.
By the way i love espresso, so don't hesitate to leave a tip if you like =D

If you are inexperienced with slicer setting, I recommend this one for ...
Ender 3: https://www.fatdragongames.com/fdgfiles/cura-ender-3-5-profiles-work-cr-10/
Bambu A1 Printer: https://www.fatdragongames.com/fdgfiles/bambu-studio-slicer-profiles-a1-mini-3d-printer/

"Every battlefield the Hostile Environment Troops find themselves on, is a hostile, bombarded and chemically saturated one. Taking trenches, cities and sectors require troops in the thousands, and waiting for weeks or months on end for the right moment to strike. To that end, Command uses Shock Assault Troops, Specialists in lightning warfare.

Other armies decorate these soldiers in honors, having them as elite regiments on their planets. The best of the best.
Not so for the Hostile Environment Troops, for in the hellish condition they find themselves in, a simple hole in their suits means they are living on borrowed time.
Most, but not all, Shock Assault are penal legionaires, promised freedom if they survive a single attack on an enemy position. Very few survive to see reinforcements, fewer still survive long enough for a commissar to excuse them of their sins and turn them free men and women.

The life of a Shock Assault Trooper is a short and deadly life, but their sacrifices turn the tide of battle, saving thousands.

Enlist Today!"

I have always been a big fan of the stealers of genetics from a popular board game set on a drifting, abandoned hulk in space, especially the early plastic ones with the humped back and ribbed muscles. I first came across them as soul stealers for the now OOP game Space Crusade.

I've also always wanted to do larger, warrior variants, compatible with space bugs from the world's most popular grim-dark tabletop wargame. So I've sculpted one - my first real organic sculpt. Still learning, but this has been a fun project. Fits with standard xenos warrior bits.

This file is only the torso. Pictured bits are for illustrative purposes only.

You can download compatible heads here: https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/soul-stealer-warrior-head-bit

And classic 'Soul Stealer' style arms are available as part of this model: https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/soul-stealer-purestrain-poseable-arms

UPDATE: Had a suggestion of a version with smoother ribbing, so added it as an alternative design.

This is a remix of the attached Triceratops model mixed with the Ewok Catapult (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4773367). I modeled the ammo bags and ropes for the catapult, as well as the leather strapping and harnesses, and enhanced the detail of everything in Zbrush. The triceratops' pose was adjusted slightly to get the catapult to not bang into his frill.

I sized this for a 40x80mm base for Hordes of the Things/ Fantasy Rules! (yes the ! is part of the name). I left the harness option in for people who want to risk printing it at it's current size, or who may want to embiggen it for display or to make a huge 28mm scale model. This one is sized roughly for my 10mm mass battle lizardman army.

Here are twelve, perhaps crude, though definitely brutal close combat hand-to-hand melee assault weapons. They are intended to allow give you some extra options and conversion bits for your Chaos Cultists. You do love Chaos Cultists don't you?? Though I think they are generic enough to work for most human sized miniatures in any grim and dark dystopian future setting from undercity gangs, to wasteland scavengers, rebels, organized criminal thugs, and pretty much any kind of poorly equipped ne'er-do-wells up to no good.

Here are the 12 unique weapons:

-- Axe
-- Club
-- Hammer1
-- Hammer2
-- Knife1
-- Knife2
-- Mace
-- Pick
-- Pipe
-- Scimitar
-- Sword1
-- Sword2

Each weapon comes in three STL variants:
1) weapon by itself
2) weapon held in a right hand
3) weapon held in a right hand (hand has a nub to socket into wrists)

Knife1 and Knife2 have four variants each, two with the blade held normally and two with the blade held ready to stab. You can mirror the weapons with hands on them to create left-handed versions. All total that comes to 68 different options. You can use these files for physical or digital conversions as you see fit. They are also Creative Common Licensed so that you can modify them as you please and then share your own innovations.

Enjoy, and may the Dark Gods favor you.

Inspired by the new Votann (return of the squats ;-) i had a reason to finally paint my classic squats in combination with new Votann as one big army.
Being an Epic player with a big Squat army, i also wanted to have a land train for both my squats in 40k and for Necromunda, for that is where squats live.
The Space Dwarf Land Train from taaz was a good basis and from there i made a Land Train 2.0 that i tried to give a post-squat and pre-votann vibe.

I upgraded the train-cars with printable tracks and more details (doors, windows, exhaust pipes, new towbars). Then i added runes to get several different looking train-cars.
Furthermore i made new train-car tops because i wanted a different (lower) height and a more detailed weapon design.

Finally and most importantly i completely redesigned the train engine.
It now also is a playable piece of terrain and has details that fit a model this size in 40k.
The sides are based on the sides from the original from taaz, also as a tribute/thanks, but the rest is redesigned from the ground up.

All STL are tested/printed in 40k scale (0.2mm 15% infill) and printable, most of them supportless.

When building Gore Krusha Mega Walkers, greenskin Meks sometimes opt to build massive klanky klaws as melee weapons instead of the often-seen giant saws.


FOR BEST QUALITY PRINT, PLEASE READ ALL(!) OF BELOW:

This highly detailed Klaw Arm is compatible to my Gore Krusha's Mega Walker
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/gore-krusha-mega-walker

I REALLY recommend a layer high of 0.050 or lower for all parts to get the quality I intended.
Please see the pics of my print, those are all in FDM (0,05mm layer height)!

I tried to keep the need of tree supports low, but I recommend it to use them on some parts - decide for yourself & make sure to set the tree support z-distance to a multiple of 2 (layer height) for optimal removal (keep in mind: layer height 0.05 to 0.075(!) )


----------------------------------------------------------------------
-------------- EXCEPTIONAL 'fings for this model: --------------------
----------------------------------------------------------------------

---------- MOVABLE PARTS ----------
- Most pivot points are actually functional, pose the arm as you want!
- I have included a functional hydraulics option for the klaw, so it can move once assembled.
 -> You need a well calibrated printer to get this hydraulics working. Print all *FlexHydraulics*.stl with wallcount = e.g. 99 to get a massive print without infill.
 -> For the FlexHydraulics pins you need to cut of ca. 10mm of regular 1,75mm filament. (I did not test this in resin, but I guess you could print them)
 -> As an option to the FlexHydraulics there are two fixed versions. Have a look in the parts.
- Print all PINS with wallcount = e.g. 99 to get a massive print without infill.

---------- CABLES and WIRES ----------

KlawArm_03 Bits come with an option to glue in some wires (or filament).
If you use some 0,75mm² or 0,5mm² electrical wires the arm could still be movable :)

---------- Arm on the LEFT or RIGHT? ----------
You can print all parts normally except the shoulder pauldrons. (because of the flat printing side)
-> You have to mirror both pauldrons if you want the arm on the left side of your model (from your point of view)

---------- ASSEMBLY ----------

If you need instructions - just open all files in 3D Builder or e.g. Meshmixer. There you can look where they need to go.

---------- FOLLOWING: ----------

Shame less beggin' for some coins for caffeine I need doin' stuff like that :-)

Please consider a tip ....this highly detailed model was a work of 80h+ of free time!
If you do so, I HIGHLY APPRECIATE YOUR GENEROSITY :-)

Kind regards,
Tersus

Commentary :

All of the design backgrounds were based on the Roguetrader (1st Edition) and the 2nd and 3rd Edition designs.

As always, based on the design of the time, I mixed the design sensibilities of the present era.

Personally, I recommend that the size of the shoulder pad is 105-108%, and the size of the head is 95%. (That looks good.)

I got a lot of help from my colleague, LegioXIVguy, in determining the ratio and size. So the overall size is about between New edition Chaos space marines and Primaris marines.

Gore Krushas are build by the biggest and craziest meks at the peak of a greenskin WAAAAAGH! as a symbol of their gods - Towering over the battlefield this 'eavy armored walker krushes smaller enemies by simply stomping them to bloody goo (with insane laughter from the Gore Kursha Kaptin').
Meanwhile larger targets can be engaged with it's mega chain choppa, ripping through armor easily.
Although not very accurate, the Gore Krushas ranged weapons have 'nuff shootin' to hit and kill all targets. The sound of high kaliber gattlas at full auto bursts is horrifying or at least intimidating for the most enemies (....or motivating in case of greenskin ears)


FOR BEST QUALITY PRINT, PLEASE READ ALL(!) OF BELOW:

To print the Gore Krusha Mega Walker, you need time or a large resin printer ;-)
I REALLY recommend a layer high of 0.075 or lower for all parts to get the quality I intended.
Please see the pics, those are all printed in FDM (<=0,075mm)!

I tried to keep the need of tree supports low, but I recommend it to use them on some parts - decide for yourself & make sure to set the tree support z-distance to a multiple of 2 (layer hight) for optimal removal (keep in mind: layer hight 0.05 to 0.075(!) )
(The Mega Choppa should be printed with tree support, I included a version with the teef supported, this is also tested)

----------------------------------------------------------------------
-------------- EXCEPTIONAL 'fings for this model: --------------------
----------------------------------------------------------------------

---------- SPIKES ----------

Print them "laying", not standing, or else they will easily snap of if you ram another model ;-)

---------- Exhausts ----------

"GoreKrusha_Exhausts02_Bars_1.75mmFilament.stl" can be combined with "GoreKrusha_Exhausts02.stl" for Resin printers.
In FDM just use some 1.75mm filament & make sure you don't snap of the middle post - trust me :D

---------- LEGS ----------

The legs can be posed standing or walking, but I recommend standing for both to find a good balance for the model.

---------- ARMS ----------

- !!! All joints MUST be printed laying flat !!! This is important, else they will likely snap of due to the weight of the arms.
- The arms should fit thight, but they are not perfect, better glue them after posing
- The ammo belt is a "flexi" print-in-place, once finished, you can gently move the joints to breake it free. With this, the dakka arm can be posed freely as you want.

---------- DA RIGGAZ (Crew) ----------

- Da Riggaz are posed and remixed from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3985624 by poikilos
- To print Da Riggaz you need tree supports, I flipped them back 15° or 30° (depending on the model) and lifted them +1,5mm on the Z-axies, so the supports will pe printed first. Layer hight 0.05mm, enable support roof with ~0.75mm.

---------- Over all printing recommendation! ----------

- I printed the bottom plate with 25% infill, since it has to carry the weight of the model (about 1,2kg!)
- Many parts have a "flat surface" -> face those to the build plate.
- Detaild sides / most visible sides should be faced towards the cooling fan.

---------- ASSEMBLY ----------

If you need instructions - just open all files in 3D Builder or e.g. Meshmixer. There you can look where they go.

Quite a bit larger than an Imperial Baneblade, a Kill Grinda Mega Fortress is truly a fearsome idol of the brutish Ork gods:
On massive, krushin' trakks, armed with weapons capable of destroying entire hab blocks with one shot, they rumble onwards, where da fORKtress Kaptains points them to.
Only the most powerful Warbosses have 'nuff teef to pay the bestest meks to build these mega-super-heavy assault vehicles.

An IMPORTANT note for the scale :D
- Quote of an imperial agent during a massive Ork encounter on Fungusius Primus:
"Big Mek Gutgrinda once build this thing at a scale of a Baneblade (~79%).... he was KRUSHED and GRINDED brutally to deff by WAAAGHBOSS Gobba Gitkrusha's 'GORKAfORKress' (100% scale)" ;-)



----------------------------------------------------------------------
------- FOR BEST PRINT QUALITY , PLEASE READ ALL(!) OF BELOW: --------
----------------------------------------------------------------------

I REALLY recommend a layer hight of 0.075 or lower for all parts to get the quality I intended.
Please see the pics, those are all printed in FDM (<=0,075mm)!

All parts are printed without tree supports, some parts don't need supports, but please decide for your self. :)

----------------------------------------------------------------------
---------------- EXCEPTIONAL 'fings for this model: ------------------
----------------------------------------------------------------------

---------- Over all printing recommendation! ----------

Many parts have a "flat surface" -> face those to the build plate. Keep in mind, the z-axies does the detailed job!
Detailed sides / most visible sides should be faced towards the cooling fan.

The supa gattla can fit two 5x3mm magnet to be rotatable. The "KillGindaMegaFortress_SupaGattla_Pin.stl" does a similar job, but not as good, I guess... although I never tested the magnets.

The main gun can be assembled in 3 ways:
- Mega Zzappa
- Nukular Shell (with or without spacer, as you like)
- None of both

I printed the supa gattla ammo without a raft, but if you have problems with adhesion, use a raft.
-> If you have concerns about the sharp corners of the ammo belt in FMD, you have the right feeling, but "in the end it doesn't matter", you will not see this issue after assembly.
-> enable "print thin walls" in cura or equivalent in your slicer.

Arrange the lobbas ("KillGrindaMegaFortress_Lobbas02 - 07 & _LazerMarker) as you like, view all files in e.g. 3D Builder or Meshmixer to see how I designed them. The "Lazer sight"-bit is optional, you can replace it with an additional lobba as you like.

---------- Assembly ----------

All parts have a arritation point, so just "move" them until they snap or feel right.
- If you need instructions: just open all files in 3D Builder or e.g. Meshmixer. There you can look where all parts belong to.

Not the best weapon for Smaller Knights, but I am a completionist. This is the last one on my list.

The C-Beamer is a relic weapon usually overlooked because it does more damage the farther away the target is, and less up close, which is a disadvantage on the close-range, terrain-choked tabletops of the current edition.

But, it's free. ;)

Supported versions have a lot of tiny sub-supports that you will want to flick out after curing, especially on barrel 3. It seemed the only way to save that spiraling effect.

You might not be able to access or paint the interior cages of barrels 2 or 3. If that is unacceptable, I recommend barrel 1. It's cleaner and sleeker.

Everything is included from the shoulder socket down.

Ball and socket upper arms are included, in case you want to keep a fixed, glued pose.

I recommend the flat-elbowed upper arms, and magnetizing with an 8mm x 2mm or 8mm x 3mm neodymium magnet glued to the fused upper arm, and steel magnets glued to the elbow "socket" of the weapon.

I usually glue a steel BB in the socket, then cap it with a pair of glued-on steel washers. See pics for reference.

You'll lose some poseability, but gain modularity.

Also, check out my other mech and knight parts, most of which are free.
https://cults3d.com/en/users/johnbearross/creations

Enjoy!

Want to fire some flesh eatin' short range artillery ammunishun that's not a bug?? Rukka Buggys are your vehicle of choice! Slap it! Expolode it!
"How much bity or 'splodin' flesh balls you want to shoot??" - "Yes."


FOR BEST QUALITY PRINT, PLEASE READ ALL(!) OF BELOW:

To print the Rukka Buggy, you need time or a resin printer ;-)
I REALLY recommend a layer high of 0.075mm or lower for all parts to get the quality I intended.
Please see the pics, those are all printed in FDM (<=0,075mm)!

I highly recommend it to use tree supports (at least on the crew) - make sure to set the tree support z-distance to a multiple of 2 (layer hight) for optimal removal (keep in mind: layer hight 0.05 (crew) or 0.075mm (buggy))

---------- Over all printing recommendation (FDM) ----------

- Many parts have a flat surface -> face those to the build plate. Print slow (25mm/s)
- Detaild sides / most visible sides should be faced towards the cooling fan.
- Crew should be printed with tree supports, rotated 45° back (so the face is up). Support Z-distance should be a multiple of 2 to 3 of the layer hight (0.05 - 0.075mm). PRINT SLOW - Outer wall max 25mm/s. You want dem details gooood!

The most difficult parts (actually not the Gobbo Crew...):
- "RuckaBuggy_Rear_02.stl": you need to be super carefull to remove tree supports (they are needed). My test print broke on the bars while removing them. I was able to glue it back on (tip: smooth cracks with a lighter)
- "RuckaBuggy_Front_04.stl": failed 4 times while removing tree supports, combined with other parts. I needed to print this part as a single part with normal supports.

---------- Assembly ----------

If you need instructions - just open all files in 3D Builder or e.g. Meshmixer. There you can look where they go.
Some parts are press fits (e.g. the wheels) you don't need to glue them, unless you print in resin (not tested).
I recommend to "dry fit" the parts with blu tack or a similar reusable putty.


---------- FOLLOWING: ----------

Shame less beggin' for => "Tossin' a coin to your Tersus...." :D

Please consider a tip ....this highly detailed model was a work of many hours of free time!
If you do so, I HIGHLY APPRECIATE YOUR GENEROSITY :-) :-) :-)

Kind regards,
Tersus

With the mysterious Dark Powers making their once-hidden presence more known, new, sinister mech designs have begun to appear on the battlefields of the Junctionworld inter-reality gate networks.

Notable among these new nightmares is a tailed, tentacled monstrosity labeled by intel operatives at the Mercenary Guild as Project Abby.

These warped, spiked, and twisted armors are malevolent in form and purpose. They have a heat cannon on one arm as their primary ranged weapon, while the melee component of their arsenal is composed of an energized whip weapon system. Crackling with plasma, this cluster of mechanical tentacles can be used to impale, crush, or slice through enemy targets. The Abby features a tail-like appendage that performs the same function, protecting the armored walker from the rear.

Project Abby mechs also seem to be nesting grounds for ScytheBots, verminous robot drones that seem to claim the dreaded hulks as mobile nests. These hive-like bots provide a symbiotic layer of protection for the mech, cutting down infantry that venture too close.

The Gorkabot is a massive armored mech, built as an effigy of a greenskin god! Armed to da teef da Gorkabot krushes all kind of ememys with it's klaw while shredding infantry with hails of bullets from the DAKKA-Storm gun.


In the Gorkabots belly is space for a few greenskins to pop out, if the time is good for some krumpin'!








FOR BEST QUALITY PRINT, PLEASE READ ALL(!) OF BELOW:





To print the Gorkabot, you need time or a resin printer ;-)


I REALLY recommend a layer high of 0.075 or lower for all parts to get the quality I intended.


Please see the pics, those are all printed in FDM (<=0,075mm)!





I tried to keep the need of tree supports low, but I highly recommend it to use them - make sure to set the tree support z-distance to a multiple of 2 (layer hight) for optimal removal (keep in mind: layer hight 0.05 to 0.075(!) )








----------------------------------------------------------------------


-------- EXCEPTIONAL 'fings for this model: ----------


----------------------------------------------------------------------








---------- COMPATIBILITY ----------





Arms and legs should be compatible to my Mega Bots (not testet)





---------- MAIN BODY ----------





"GorkaBot_Belly.stl" prints without tree support! Just use regular supports.


"GorkaBot_Torso.stl" prints without tree support! Just use regular supports. flip the model slightly to the back (see Cura screenshot)


The doors should be printed without supports with a brim (see Cura screenshot)





---------- LEGS ----------





The legs are unique, there is an individual model for the right / left leg. Those are mirrorable / interchangeable if you want.





---------- ARMS----------





The arms should fit 10x4mm magnets (not tested) but also have a ball joint for more posability...





The "GorkaBot_Klaw_Arm_02.stl" should be printed 45° "floating 1,5mm in the air" see my Cura screenshot - this will give you the best quality result!





---------- Over all printing recommendation! ----------





Many parts have a "flat surface" -> face those to the build plate.


Detaild sides / most visible sides should be faced towards the cooling fan.





---------- Assembly ----------





if you need instructions - just open all files in 3D Builder or e.g. Meshmixer. There you can look where they go








---------- FOLLOWING: ----------





Shame less beggin' for some coins for coffein I need doin' stuff like that :-D ;-)





Please consider a tip ....this highly detailed model was a work of 100h+ of free time!


If you do so, I HIGHLY APPRECIATE YOUR GENEROSITY :-) :-) :-)





Kind regards,


Tersus

The Skrappin' Mega Bot is a stompin' armored Mech capable of moving objects without any efforts using it's powerfull trakktor kannon! Dead 'ard

killy saws tear apart every enemy getting to close. Once the Skrappin' Mega Bot krushed some enemy vehicles, turing those into piles of skrapp, it 

can do some quick n' dirty fixin' jobs on allied vehicles or mechs.


FOR BEST QUALITY PRINT, PLEASE READ ALL(!) OF BELOW:

Beneath my Krumpin' Mega Bot this is one of my most detailed models until now!

To print this monster, you need time or a resin printer ;-)
I REALLY recommend a layer high of 0.075 or lower for all parts to get the quality I intended, while designing this model - please see the pics, those

are printed in FDM (<=0,075mm)!

I tried to keep the need of tree supports low, but I highly recommend it to use them - make sure to set the tree support z-distance to a multiple of 2

(layer hight) for optimal removal (keep in mind: layer hight 0.05 to 0.075(!) )

For a few bitz I added a resin version with "_Resin" in the file name - unlike the FDM versions those don't have a flat bottom. (I have not test printed 

these files, but they should be good to go!)

The Trakktor Kannon can be a variant of an actuall (rattling) Kannon, as it lifts up 'eavy objects and throw them with a high velocity to enemy gitz - 

less explosiv, more smashin' - same damage! ;-)

----------------------------------------------------------------------
---------- EXCEPTIONAL 'fings for this model: ----------
----------------------------------------------------------------------


---------- COMPATIBILITY ----------

Most parts are compatible to my Krumpin' Mega Bot, so you can build your variant as you like :)
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/krumpin-mega-bot

---------- MAIN BODY ----------

You CAN use two 10x4mm Neodym magnets for the junction "hip <> main hull" to get a rotatable/removable body!
As an alternative to the magnets print the file "ScrappinMegaBot_Hip02.stl"

---------- LEGS ----------

The legs are unique, there is a individual model for the right / left leg. Those are mirrorable / interchangeable if you want.

---------- Over all printing recommendation! ----------

Many parts have a "flat surface" - face those to the build plate.

---------- FOLLOWING: ----------

Shame less beggin' for some coins for coffein I need doin' stuff like that :-D ;-)

Please consider a tip ....this HIGH detailed model was a work of 80h+ of free time!
This model is not a simple remix, all parts of my Krumpin' Mega Bot have been reviewed and altered with new details! :-)
If you do so, I HIGHLY APPRECIATE YOUR GENEROSITY :-) :-):-)

Kind regards,
Tersus

Ring - Infil to add weight, supports needed for spade inset. Letter embossing doesn't need it.
Spade - Infil to add weight, no supports
Letters - Print flat, already scaled to fit nicely in the embossing
Star - Infil to add weight.

Full print with 4x4x4 walls/top/bottom and 38% infil came to about 48g in weight.

Glue in lettering and spade. Star may need minor sanding but should push fit into the space tightly and not need anything else to secure it.

UPDATE: Found there was some geometry present in heads 1 and 2 for each type that may present problems, so I went through and cleaned it out. If you printed these with resin before, should be wary of little pockets of resin within the mouth. New ones do not have these voids.

There are a lot of orcish heads about this website, but I wanted to make my own. I started by putting together some shapes, mostly toruses and squished spheres, in the general form I wanted compared to available orcish heads, and then sculpted the finer details, until I was happy enough to make multiple expressions from it.

I couldn't settle on a specific nose or teeth type, so I decided to use both in extra combos with all the facial expressions I sculpted, resulting in twenty, 20, different head combinations.

I wanted something that could be used for a number of orcish plans I have coming up, something that could work for more warfam figures that I may produce. Panzerfauste, the fantasy ww2 with british orcs, is a game these could be used for.

Have fun with them and be creative all!

I want to thank you folks for helping me reach 500 followers after only a month of paid sales.

As a token of appreciation, here's the RFBC-500 Avtomat Pushka (sorry, my computer-translated Russian is terrible), an Automatic Rifle Cannon (RFBC proxy).

It's available in both Right (A) and Left (B) versions, with the main weapon body having a choice of stick or drum magazine.

Also, one of my heavy stubby gatlings is incorporated into the design. That asymmetric part of the design is a nice feature, in my opinion.

A pair of weapon arms, long and short, are supplied, as well as upper arms at a variety of angles for magnetization.

I glue the ball and sockets together, then glue 12mm x 2mm magnets to the bottom of the upper arm.

An 8mm x 2mm magnet will fit in the face of the main weapon body. I usually glue in washers in the barrel section. 4mm inner diameter/9mm outer diameter washers usually do it, or #6 washers. Or just glue them together and print more.

You can use opposing magnets in the weapon arms (remember opposite poles) to the new upper arms. I recommend 12mm x 3mm magnets.

Enjoy, and thanks again! More good stuff to come.

Best,
JBR

The Krumpin' Mega Bot is a hulking, heavily armored monster! Pistons, welded to powerful close combat weapons, such as the Ripper Klaw deliver enormous hydraulik power to every git or vehicle gettin' to close.
Other than the more commonly Deff Bots and or Kans, Krumpin' Mega Bots are usually armed with high speed rattling weapons of high calibers to kill enemies even before reaching them in close combat! (Or just to make horrible loud noise...)

EDIT: Most Parts are compatible to my Skrappin' Mega Bot
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/skrappin-mega-bot
Build your Bot as you like! :-)

FOR BEST QUALITY PRINT, PLEASE READ ALL(!) OF BELOW:

This is my ambitious model until now!

To print this monster, you need time or a resin printer ;-)
I REALLY recommend a layer high of 0.075 or better for all parts to get the quality I intended, while designing this model - please see the pics, those are printed in FDM

(<=0,075mm)!

I tried to keep the need of tree supports low, but I highly recommend it to use tree supports - make sure to set the tree support z-distance to a multiple of 2 for optimal removal

(keep in mind: layer hight 0.05 to 0.075(!) )

For the Rippa Klaw I added a resin version with "_Resin" in the file name - unlike the FDM versions those don't have a flat bottom. (I have not test printed these files, but they

should be good to go!)

----------------------------------------------------------------------
---------- EXCEPTIONAL 'fings for this model: ----------
----------------------------------------------------------------------


---------- GUN ARM: ----------

THE RATTLA KANNON MAGAZINE IS ROTATABLE IF DONE AS INTENDED!!

For the axies you simply insert usual filament!
If you don't glue the "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_06.stl" to "...05.stl" the "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag.stl" is interchangeable - who knows what might be released in future...... ;-)
-> If you don't want this or don't have filament, just glue the parts as wanted.


Assembly as followed: (please see also the last two pics/screenshots!

1. Stick (NOT glue, if you want it to be removable) together:
"MegaBot_RattlerKannon_05" & "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_06", OPTIONAL: "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Barrel.stl"

2. Insert a 1.75mm filament (42mm long - as the answer to all questions, lol) into "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag_Back_Spacer.stl", large side first, followed by

"MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag".

2.a) Glue on all parts of "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag_Back.stl", if you want more realistic details (even if Ork xD).
2.a.note: Warning: print "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag_Back.stl" with "brim" 3mm+.
They will, regardless of brim width, fall apart after removing the brim. This is intended so you can glue them bitz more random on the Mag!

3. "Dry fit" (NO glue at first!) all parts

3.a) View the last two pics (Tinkercad screenshots)!

3.b) "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Trigger.stl" to
 "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag_Back_Spacer.stl"

3.c) I recommend to glue in "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_TriggerPin.stl" to "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Trigger.stl" first.

3.d) Glue the filament between "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Trigger.stl" & "MegaBot_RattlerKannon_Mag_Back_Spacer.stl"


---------- MAIN BODY ----------

You CAN use two 10x4mm Neodym magnets for the junction "hip <> main hull" to get a rotatable/removable body!

---------- LEGS ----------

The legs are unique, there is a individual model for right / left leg. Those are mirrorable / interchangeable.

---------- Over all printing recommendation! ----------

Many parts have a "flat surface" - face those to the build plate.


---------- FOLLOWING: ----------

Shame less beggin' for some coins for coffein I need doin' stuff like that :-D ;-)

Please consider a tip ....this HIGH detailed model was a work of 100h+ of free time (~50 RL days)! If you do so, I HIGHLY APPRECIATE YOUR GENEROSITY :-) :-):-)

Kind regards,
Tersus

Hail, Fellow Scions!

The standard Thermal Cannon that comes from the factory is nice, but I wanted a little bit more.

This matches my alternate carapace gun from my other designs.

I magnetize my Knights at the elbow. There's is a socket there for whatever method you prefer. There are two parts...

1-The Main Gun. I print in a vertical orientation. It takes time, but the barrels don't have droop or supports on them.
2.The Optional Gunshield. This is notched to allow the cannon's sensors to view past it, but still provides a bit of cover.

The gunshield slips over the two barrels of the cannon, and should be glued. Some fitting may be required, depending on your printer.

Make sure you send in pics of your Makes!

Instead of tips, please check out my science fiction series on Amazon. Read the preview chapters, and if you like it, download the ebook.

Armored mech warfare in the arenas and streets of a place called Junctionworld!

Five parts, supported and clean.

1 separate missile warhead (print multiple).

1 standard launcher base that should mount to unmagnetized knights with a 2mm plug.

Rigged version of an ork made by VidovicArts. I used this to create all my ork models so far.

There are a some hidden parts in the file and lots of poses in the pose library of the rig. My workflow with this is as follows:

-Add objects like torsi an weapons to the file an pot them to the right place at the body
-hide all parts you don't need for your boi
-make copy of the rig, the body and all parts you added
-parent all objects to the rig (as objects to specific bones)
-choose a pose from the pose library or create a new one.
-apply all modifiers to the parts
-unparent all objects while keeping their transformation
-boolean unite all objects
-use windows 3D builder to repair any problems in the mesh
-print

Four included poses and a builder to do your own. Happy printing!

Rigged version of an ork made by VidovicArts. I used this to create all my ork models so far.

There are a some hidden parts in the file and lots of poses in the pose library of the rig. My workflow with this is as follows:

-Add objects like torsi an weapons to the file an pot them to the right place at the body
-hide all parts you don't need for your boi
-make copy of the rig, the body and all parts you added
-parent all objects to the rig (as objects to specific bones)
-choose a pose from the pose library or create a new one.
-apply all modifiers to the parts
-unparent all objects while keeping their transformation
-boolean unite all objects
-use windows 3D builder to repair any problems in the mesh
-print

Death comes in many forms. For this death, it's a ball. Also includes 2 genetic gathering and sampling assistants for free.

For a Devilfish, it's the wrong shape, wrong size, wrong weapon options, and can't technically carry any Kroot, but it's lovely just the same. This was supposed to be a simple joke project that got out of hand. The level of detail isn't the same all over but it's taken up too much of my time and I just need to move on. 

* Comes with open and closed version of the side and back hatches.
* It can either be assembled using 1.75mm filament as alignment pins or 10x2mm magnets.
* Magnets allow for easy breakdown to swap open/closed hatches or easier travel.
* Sides can be printed mirrored for more variety.


You will need heads to complete these models. I recommend purchasing the official box sets for those. Hopefully this will tell THEM that we want more options to add them to our armies. Alternately, if you have a resin printer, another modeler has made these: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4011591

Check out my printed models for sale: https://www.etsy.com/shop/MasterShaperFelix

"What are you Hungry?. I just fell down a hill. I'm soaking wet. I don't have any food. I have no food on me. I have nothing on me." -Dennis Nedry

This is a Model requested by TedStark,CH35C0, and many more on Thingiverse (yep, I take requests) After I posted my original (no frills) Dilophosaurus model seen here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3380098

If this proves popular, I will work on some other Dinosaurs and Prehistoric Creatures,as well as accessories and variants of this model if requested. I could possibly do things like
the fully body,battle wounds, dino-rider armor, a wall mountable bust, a water base. So Please post your makes, hit like, and provide feedback on what you would like to see in the comments

Dilophosaurus is a genus of theropod dinosaur that lived in what is now North America during the Early Jurassic, about 193 million years ago. Length was up to 23 ft long and an estimated Mass of 880 lbs.

Jurassic Park brought new recognition to the Dilophosaurus, being one of the coolest brought to life for the first film as well as my personal favorite. The Jurassic Park version shows a smaller version (could just be younger) that spit blinding venom, and had a frill that would unfurl when attacking, none of which are supported by the fossil record but did make a heck of a entertaining film so I am ok with it.

We at Ill Gotten Games are big fans of the [Vintage RPG Podcast](https://www.stitcher.com/podcast/unwinnable-3/the-vintage-rpg-podcast), and after designing a model for Hambone [the hammer-wielding ranger, Johan](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3483772)), I made one for Stu as well. This is Greel, an opportunistic (but deep down, gold-hearted) ex-mercenary company leader/current warlock with a magic ring that can turn him into a tree at the first sight of danger. The model prints without support.

If you haven't checked it out, Hambone and Stu (Horvath, from [unwinnable.com](https://unwinnable.com/)) do a weekly podcast where they discuss tabletop games, and do deep dives into RPGs old and new. This all branches off of Stu's excellent [Instagram feed](https://www.instagram.com/vintagerpg/?hl=en), which is always an insightful read if you're into the history and current state of tabletop roleplaying games. We're proud to be [supporting them on Patreon](https://www.patreon.com/vintagerpg/overview), and you should really check out what they're doing/throw them some bones if you like it as much as we do.

Ankylosaurus (meaning “fused lizard”) is a genus of thyreophoran dinosaur. Fossils of Ankylosaurus have been found in geologic formations dating to the very end of the Cretaceous Period, between about 68–66 million years ago, in western North America, making it among the last of the non-avian dinosaurs. It was named by Barnum Brown in 1908, and the only species classified in the genus is A. magniventris. A handful of specimens have been excavated to date, but a complete skeleton has not been discovered. Though other members of Ankylosauria are represented by more extensive fossil material, Ankylosaurus is often considered the archetypal member of its group.

The front part of the jaws were covered in a beak, with rows of small, leaf-shaped teeth further behind it. It was covered in armor plates, or osteoderms, with bony half-rings covering the neck, and had a large club on the end of its tail. Bones in the skull and other parts of the body were fused, increasing their strength, and this feature is the source of the genus name.

Compared with modern land animals the adult Ankylosaurus was very large. Some scientists have estimated a length of 11 meters (36 ft).[1] Another reconstruction suggests a much smaller size, at 6.25 m (20.5 ft) long, up to 1.5 m (5 ft) wide and about 1.7 m (5.5 ft) high at the hip.[2] Ankylosaurus may have weighed over 6,000 kilograms (13,000 lb), making it one of the heaviest armored dinosaurs yet discovered. The body shape was low-slung and quite wide. It was quadrupedal, with the hind limbs longer than the forelimbs. Although its feet are still unknown, comparisons with other ankylosaurids suggest Ankylosaurus probably had five toes on each foot. The skull was low and triangular in shape, wider than it was long. The largest known skull measures 64.5 centimeters (25 in) long and 74.5 cm (29 in) wide.[4] Their teeth were weaker than ceratopsid and hadrosaurid dinosaurs of the time, so they probably chewed very little.

Parasaurolophus was a hadrosaurid, part of a diverse family of Cretaceous dinosaurs known for their range of bizarre head adornments. This genus is known for its large, elaborate cranial crest, which at its largest forms a long curved tube projecting upwards and back from the skull. Charonosaurus from China, which may have been its closest relative, had a similar skull and potentially a similar crest. Visual recognition of both species and sex, acoustic resonance, and thermoregulation have been proposed as functional explanations for the crest. It is one of the rarer hadrosaurids, known from only a handful of good specimens.

Dilophosaurus is a genus of theropod dinosaur that lived in what is now North America during the Early Jurassic, about 193 million years ago. Length was up to 23 ft long and an estimated Mass of 880 lbs.

Jurassic Park brought new recognition to the Dilophosaurus, being one of the coolest brought to life for the first film as well as my personal favorite. The Jurassic Park version shows a smaller version (could just be younger) that spit blinding venom, and had a frill that would unfurl when attacking, none of which are supported by the fossil record but did make a heck of a entertaining film so I am ok with it. This pose is meant to be reminiscent of the "fetch the stick stupid" scene in which the Dilo' looks over its shoulder at the stick. I like pose from this scene because the Dinosaur is still in its innocent puppy mode and shows off the mobility of its long neck also the frill isn't visible in that scene at all so this still fits..

You have some options to make different versions of the Dilo with the files I have provided:

 You can make a model the prints in parts that all pegs together. There is also a a high resolution fully assembled version (probably to big to properly preview with the "Thingview" sorry). It has higher quality details than most FFM printers can duplicate but if you have a resin printer or just want to play with the file to make a bigger version I feel this will be the most useful for you. I have also feature a Scaled up head it is about 1/2 the size of a real dilophosaurus or about 65%-75% the size of the Jurassic Park dilo, I printed one myself and it makes a great wall display.

[KICKSTARTER ALERT!](https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/292543184/scatterblocks)

We're currently running a Kickstarter campaign for the [extended range of our ScatterBlocks](https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/292543184/scatterblocks) (quick-assembling miniature terrain), so drop on by and drop us a pledge if you want the full range. For those of you supporting us (or thinking about supporting us) on [Patreon](https://www.patreon.com/illgottengames), all the rewards will go to our backers there as well (as we do with all our crowdfunding campaigns).

This miniature is a variant of [the one](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2803739) that will be included in our new game, [Wrath & Ruin](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MasT0o4XTCY) (currently in development), a blend of simple miniature wargaming and physical boulder-throwing (check out the videos). We're pretty excited about this one, and would love to get others in on the play testing phase before we expand and go wider with the game. Kickstarter backers at the $25 level and Patreon supporters will get the play tester kit in March (after the current campaign wraps).

The Knight, like all the miniatures we're designing for this game, prints without the need of support material. We printed ours without a raft and at a .1 layer height with 10% infill.

Enjoy!

As a huge fan of the [Peaky Blinders](http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b045fz8r) series, I couldn't resist the urge to sculpt a few of the titular gangsters. These aren't representing characters from the show, more serving as an homage/series of historical miniatures. These are a bit too detailed for FDM printing (though I'd love to be proven wrong) but I'll be ordering some from [Obsessively Geek over at 3Dhubs](https://www.3dhubs.com/new-york/hubs/obsessively-geek) who does some amazing SLA-printed prototypes for us on a regular basis, and I'll post some makes/painted versions soon.

We've set up a [Patreon page](https://www.patreon.com/illgottengames) for anyone who's interested in helping to fund us so we can keep making free and open sourced games like Pocket-Tactics, Wayfarer Tactics. and others, not to mention the growing catalog of gaming miniatures that you can use for whatever you want! (Psst... we take requests and commissions...)

Enjoy!

This is a Triceratops scan from artec3d.com's gallery. I reduced the mesh from the original and converted the file to STL.

This model requires supports, but the support marks aren't too much of a problem since they're out of sight on the underside and the skin texture also hides them.

I kept the mesh resolution high enough that you should be able to scale this even larger with good results. The size of this model is about 7 inches long by 3 inches high, and I estimate that my Replicator 2 could print it up to 50% larger.

As famine struck the dark forests of Jotunheim, Wolf-Eater scaled the impossible cliffs of Ymir's Brow, descending into the lowlands of Midgard and sating his hunger on the tribes of men.

I wanted to make a proper Norse dragon. I really liked the idea of an antlered forest wyrm with vestigial wings adapted to climbing giant trees. Currently using this guy as the center of an RPG storyline. He's scaled to 15mm (making him rather massive) so he can be used with my Pocket-Tactics models, but he'd make a good dragon for heroic scale (25-30mm gaming) as well.
